title: Here Is The Frankly Ridiculous List Of Everything Coming To Disney+ At Launch
text:
If this family attempted to watch everything available on day one of Disney+, at least half of them would be dead by the time they were finished. (Image: Disney)

We already knew that Disney was using all of its megacorp might to bring an absurd amount of archival content to launch its new streaming service with. Now, we finally know just what will be arriving day one, and hoo boy, folks: it’s a lot.

Editor's Note: While this list has been confirmed by Disney, regional differences are so far unclear. It may be that Australians get all of this list or only part — stay tuned for more news.

Tuesday, the official Disney+ Twitter account dropped a brief trailer highlighting just some of the films and TV that will be available — not just new and original content like The Mandalorian, but the vast library of series and films from the company’s near-century’s worth of old material.

It. Is. Time. From Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs to The Mandalorian, check out basically everything coming to #DisneyPlus in the U.S. on November 12. Pre-order in the U.S. at https://t.co/wJig4STf4P today: https://t.co/tlWvp23gLF pic.twitter.com/0q3PTuaDWT — Disney+ (@disneyplus) October 14, 2019

Then, the account went completely, absolutely, entirely insane.

In what has to be one of the longest threads — if not the longest thread — ever made on Twitter, over the course of several hours the Disney+ account proceeded to tweet, in chronological release order, every single movie, documentary, and TV series that will be available as part of the launch line up. It is dense. It is deep.

Some of it we already knew. Half of the titles available don’t seem like they’re actually real things, and we’re just witness to a truly inconceivable level of trolling. It’s a horrifyingly damning statement about the sheer depth of content that Disney owns in its vaults.

As if this wasn’t ridiculous enough, once the account was finally done tweeting — a process that took just shy of three hours — it promised more announcements about what subscribers can expect to see on the service beyond launch soon:

We ????did ????that. ???? And the announcements aren't even over yet... Stay tuned for more soon! — Disney+ (@disneyplus) October 14, 2019

Which makes sense, as there are definitely some notable absences from this list, including aspects of Fox’s back catalogue post-merger, several of the more recent Marvel movies, and Lucasfilm titles like Solo: A Star Wars Story and Star Wars: The Last Jedi, both of which were already confirmed as coming to the service at a later date.

Disney+ launches in the Australia on November 19. You could, apparently, spend the next several decades of your life watching everything on there, and that’s before they even start adding the new content we know is on the way. Which I suppose is what Bob Iger really wants, anyway?
